5. Bc4 Nf6 6. Nge2 Bd6 7. d4 O-O 8. Be3 Kh8 9. O-O c6 10. dxc6
Nxc6 11. a3 a6 12. Qd2 Ne7 13. Ba2 b5 14. Nd1 Ng6 15. b3 a5
16. c4 bxc4 17. bxc4 Bxa3 18. d5 Qd6 19. Nd4 Bc5 20. Nb5 Qb6
21. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 22. Qd4 Qxd4+ 23. Nxd4 Rd8 {Played probably
with the view of stopping the advance of either the 'd' or
c-pawn.} 24. Ne3 Ne7 {This is judicious, as it checked the
progress of the c-pawn, which, if allowed to march on, would
have proved irresistable.} 25. Rfd1 Ra6 26. Rab1 {Well played,
insuring the effective advance of the bishop's pawn.} g6
27. c5 Nfxd5 28. Nxd5 Nxd5 29. Nb5 {Gaining a piece.} Rc6 {Any
attempt to save the piece would have been vain; for if ...Be6
Nc7 gains a clear piece; and if ...Bb7, White's reply of Nc3
would have proved decisive.} 30. Rxd5 Rxd5 31. Bxd5 Rxc5
32. Ba2 1/2-1/2